</div>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-Process">Process</h2>
<p>The workflow <strong>process</strong> is the top-level description of wh=
at should happen for workflow. It is analagous to the top level of the XML =
file you can import and export from the org workflow management pages.</p>
<p>There may be multiple versions of a workflow process. When a document en=
ters workflow, it is attached to the <strong>active</strong> version. Once =
it is attached to a process version, it follows that process version, even =
if a different version becomes active. There can be only one active version=
 per document type.</p>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-Stephttp://wiki/index.php/Image:WorkflowStepScreenShot.P=
NG">Step<a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"http://wiki/index.php/Image:Work=
flowStepScreenShot.PNG" rel=3D"nofollow">http://wiki/index.php/Image:Workfl=
owStepScreenShot.PNG</a></h2>
<p>Steps bring visibility into activities. A step is a visual representatio=
n of an activity or group of activities on the "Approvals" tab of a PO. It =
offers a way to specify the name of the step, an icon to go along with it, =
and some help text for the display in workflow configuration.</p>
<p>A step might be "Departmental Approval" where each department (math and =
microbiology, for example) could have its own approval activity and associa=
ted folders.</p>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-Activity">Activity</h2>
<p>Everything that happens in workflow is carried out through an activity. =
Workflow begins with the special "START" activity, of ActivityType start. I=
t ends with the "END" activity. Activities are sequenced by ActivityRelatio=
nships, and executed particularly in that sequence.</p>
<p>When the document arrives at an activity, the activity assigns the docum=
ent to one or more folders for processing. Processing in those folders is t=
hen done by either human or robot.</p>
<h3 id=3D"Workflow-Entryrule">Entry rule</h3>
<p>Each activity between "START" and "END" is related to one step, and one =
folder. Activities may apply only in certain circumstances as set forth in =
their activity entry rules. Rules can be based on information about the doc=
ument, lines in the document, the submitter, owner, and supplier for that d=
ocument. <em>See also</em> <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"http://conflu=
ence/x/R4lh" rel=3D"nofollow">Development:Workflow Objects</a><em>.</em></p=
>
<h3 id=3D"Workflow-Folderselectionrule">Folder selection rule</h3>
<p>Another, simpler (at least in workflow configuration) set of rules gover=
ns folder selection. A few Java classes offer rules for sending documents t=
o particular folders - to individual folders for financial approval based o=
n who has what permissions, or some other set of rules. <em>See</em> <a cla=
ss=3D"external-link" href=3D"http://confluence/x/mgVz" rel=3D"nofollow">Dev=
elopment:Workflow Activity Configuration</a> <em>for details.</em></p>
<h3 id=3D"Workflow-Events">Events</h3>
<p>The "START" and "END" activities are always skipped, but they result in =
events that take care of the appropriate notifications and status changes.<=
/p>
<p>There is also an Aborted event which occurs when an order is rejected or=
 otherwise kicked out of the system.</p>
<h3 id=3D"Workflow-Connectingtofolders">Connecting to folders</h3>
<p>Because workflow folder selection rules allow an activity to route a doc=
ument to any of several folders, the activity's "FolderID" field is not a r=
eliable route between the wfFolder and wfActivity tables. A reliable route =
is by way of the wfFolderActivityInstance table.</p>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-Folder">Folder</h2>
<p>Documents languish in various folders (as configured in workflow setup) =
until they are moved along by some activity. A person may need to approve t=
he document and possibly make changes to it, or a robot may have a task to =
complete to move the document out of this folder.</p>
<p>There are shared workflow folders (created under organization setup wher=
e individuals' access is also specified) and personal folders. When a docum=
ent enters a shared folder, it is in "unassigned" state. From there, an app=
rover assigns it to their own personal folder. When it enters a personal fo=
lder (whether by manual assignment or because that was the folder specified=
 by the activity's folder selection rules), it becomes "assigned". This is =
to prevent multiple approvers from simultaneously checking up on a single o=
rder.</p>
<p>The folder selection rule for financial approvals routes to personal fol=
ders.</p>
<p>The DTD for folder configuration (http://cvs.sciquest.com/viewcvs/viewcv=
s.cgi/*checkout*/applications/docs/dtd/workflow/WorkflowFolder.dtd) sets ou=
t the possible configurations for a folder.</p>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-Robot">Robot</h2>
<p>Robots are associated with automated folders to provide actions for docu=
ments in lieu of users. If a folder is designated "automated" and a robot i=
s not associated with it, then documents will get stuck in that folder.</p>
<p>A workflow robot is implemented using 2 classes: a robot type (extends W=
orkflowRobotType) which contains metadata about the robot and is responsibl=
e for creating an instance of a class implementing WorkflowRobot interface =
which actually does the work of processing folder entry. All robot types ar=
e instantiated in AppWorkflowRobots.</p>
<p>A robot is configured using activity attributes. All robots and their at=
tributes are documented <a class=3D"external-link" href=3D"http://confluenc=
e/x/nwVz" rel=3D"nofollow">here</a>.</p>
<h2 id=3D"Workflow-SQL">SQL</h2>
<p>Each document type uses identical tables in a separate schema. A templat=
e DDL for creating a new document type is <a class=3D"external-link" href=
=3D"http://wiki/images/f/f9/WfTables.txt" rel=3D"nofollow">here</a></p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
